<h2>Solar Panels in Massachusetts</h2>
<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Massachusetts receives approximately 1,300-1,500 kWh of solar irradiance per square meter annually, with peak sun hours ranging from 3.8 in winter months to 5.2 during summer peaks. The state's solar resource is most abundant from April through October, when systems typically generate 70-75% of their annual production. Despite concerns about winter performance, modern solar panels actually operate more efficiently in cooler temperatures, and snow cover rarely impacts annual production by more than 2-3% due to the steep angle of most installations and natural snow shedding.</p>

<p>A typical 8kW residential solar system in Massachusetts can be expected to produce 9,500-11,200 kWh annually, depending on roof orientation, shading, and specific location within the state. South-facing installations with minimal shading achieve the highest production levels, while east and west-facing arrays still deliver 85-90% of optimal performance. Coastal areas including Cape Cod and the North Shore often experience slightly higher production due to increased solar clarity, while western Massachusetts may see marginal decreases due to higher elevation weather patterns. Ground-mounted systems, where space permits, can optimize tilt angles seasonally and often outperform roof-mounted installations by 10-15%.</p>

